{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646639","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646639"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:33:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:33:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18197"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18197","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18197"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.05,0.06,0.1,0.73]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10911"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79140"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10911","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10911"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18197"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64492"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25368"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25370"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79140"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following correctly describes the pathophysiology of myelomeningocele?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Defective formation of the brainstem affecting spinal cord development","Abnormal fusion of vertebral arches without neural tissue involvement","Excessive growth of neural tissue causing compression of the spinal cord","Overproduction of cerebrospinal fluid leading to spinal cord herniation","Incomplete closure of the neural tube leading to spinal cord and meninges protrusion"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMyelomeningocele is a congenital condition that results from improper development during embryogenesis. It is one of the most severe forms of neural tube defects, affecting the spinal cord and surrounding structures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pathophysiology of myelomeningocele involves the \u003Cstrong\u003Eincomplete closure of the neural tube\u003C/strong\u003E during early embryonic development. This defect allows the \u003Cstrong\u003Espinal cord and meninges to protrude\u003C/strong\u003E through an opening in the vertebral column, typically in the lumbar or sacral region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcessive growth of neural tissue causing compression of the spinal cord\u003C/strong\u003E - Myelomeningocele is due to a failure of closure, not excessive growth\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbnormal fusion of vertebral arches without neural tissue involvement\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes spina bifida occulta, a less severe form\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOverproduction of cerebrospinal fluid leading to spinal cord herniation\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not the mechanism of myelomeningocele\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDefective formation of the brainstem affecting spinal cord development\u003C/strong\u003E - Myelomeningocele is primarily a defect of the spinal cord, not the brainstem\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFolic acid supplementation before and during early pregnancy can significantly reduce the risk of neural tube defects.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Myelomeningocele is a type of neural tube defect where the spinal cord and meninges protrude through a defect in the vertebral column.","Neural tube defects occur due to incomplete closure of the neural tube during early embryonic development.","Folic acid deficiency during pregnancy is a known risk factor for neural tube defects such as myelomeningocele."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Henson B, Kadiyala B, Edens MA. Anatomy, Back, Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537074/","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Rockwood, C. A., Wirth, M. A., \u0026 Fehringer, E. V. (2016). Rockwood and Matsen\u0027s The Shoulder E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","DeSai C, Reddy V, Agarwal A. Anatomy, Back, Vertebral Column. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK525969/","Alruwaili AA, Das JM. Myelomeningocele. 2023 Jun 26. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31536302."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64492"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18197"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64492","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64492"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T15:37:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T15:38:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10911"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79140"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms